"# Chapter 1 — Transistors and Speak & Spell

Every computer you have ever touched, and every computer Motoi has
ever run on, is built from transistors. Billions of them. So we start
here.

We also start at the Texas Instruments Speak & Spell — the yellow
plastic toy from 1978 that taught a lot of American kids to spell,
including the person who built Motoi. It's a good example because it
uses the same technology as everything since, at a scale small enough
to look at end-to-end.

## What a transistor is

A transistor is a small switch made from a solid crystal, usually
silicon. It has three terminals. A voltage on one terminal — called
the base or the gate — controls whether electricity can flow between
the other two.

Say that again: a switch controlled by an electrical signal instead
of a mechanical lever.

That is the whole invention. Everything else is arrangement.

The first transistor was demonstrated at Bell Labs on December 23,
1947, by John Bardeen, Walter Brattain, and William Shockley. They
won the Nobel Prize in 1956 for it. Before transistors, computers
were built from vacuum tubes — glass bulbs the size of a light bulb,
running hot, burning out. The transistor replaced them with a
solid-state device that was smaller, cheaper, cooler, and more
reliable.

By the 1960s, engineers were putting several transistors together on
a single small piece of silicon. That's an integrated circuit — a
chip. By the 1970s they were putting thousands on one chip. By 2020
they were putting tens of billions on a chip the size of a
fingernail.

Motoi runs on chips like these. The math Motoi does happens as
voltages moving through transistors, arranged into logic gates,
arranged into adders and memory cells, arranged into a processor.
Every step is transistors.

## The Speak & Spell

Texas Instruments released the Speak & Spell in June 1978. It cost
about \\$50. It was one of the first consumer electronic devices
built around a general-purpose speech synthesizer chip.

Inside the yellow plastic case there were essentially four things:

1. A **TMS1000-family microcontroller** — a small computer chip
   containing a processor, RAM, and ROM.
2. A **TMS5100 speech synthesizer chip** — the part that made the
   sounds. This chip implemented linear predictive coding, or LPC,
   a technique for reproducing human speech from a compressed
   mathematical model of the vocal tract.
3. A **speech ROM** with the phonemes and words the toy could speak.
4. A membrane keyboard, small speaker, and vacuum-fluorescent
   display.

The important part is the TMS5100. It was one of the first single-chip
speech synthesizers, and it used a technique that would end up
underlying almost every modern speech codec (including the ones
running in cell phones today).

Linear predictive coding works like this: the human vocal tract can
be approximated mathematically as a set of resonating tubes. Given a
short sample of speech, you can figure out the coefficients that
describe the tubes at that moment. Store the coefficients (a few
bytes) instead of the raw sound (thousands of bytes), and later
re-synthesize the sound by driving the mathematical model with a
buzz-and-hiss excitation. The Speak & Spell did this in real time in
a chip designed by Larry Brantingham, Richard Wiggins, and colleagues
at TI.

Alfred, who built Motoi, learned to spell on a Speak & Spell. The
warm yellow buttons, the deterministic response, the way it made him
feel he was learning things he could hold — those are the design
principles Motoi tries to honor.

## Why we start here

Because the Speak & Spell is a computer small enough to understand
end-to-end. The whole thing is a few chips. The whole thing does one
thing. It is warm plastic in the shape of a book, with buttons, and
it teaches. That's Motoi's north star.

## A tiny example

Simulating a very simple LPC-style resonator in Motoi Scheme. This
doesn't sound like human speech — you need many more coefficients
and a proper excitation signal for that — but the mathematical shape
is here:

```
;; A single all-pole IIR filter, first order:
;;   y[n] = x[n] + a * y[n-1]
;; where 'a' controls how much of the previous sample bleeds into
;; the current one. Higher 'a' -> more resonance.

(define (make-resonator a)
  (let ((prev 0))
    (lambda (input)
      (let ((out (+ input (* a prev))))
        (set! prev out)
        out))))

(define r (make-resonator 0.9))

;; Feed it a short impulse
(r 1.0)   ;; => 1.0
(r 0.0)   ;; => 0.9
(r 0.0)   ;; => 0.81
(r 0.0)   ;; => 0.729
(r 0.0)   ;; => 0.6561
;; The impulse rings out exponentially.
```

Real LPC uses many filter coefficients simultaneously (typically ten
to twelve, updated every 20-30 milliseconds), plus an excitation
signal — either a periodic pulse (for voiced sounds like vowels) or
white noise (for hissing sounds like 's' and 'f'). The Speak & Spell
did this in dedicated silicon in 1978.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Transistors are switches. Switches make gates. Gates make adders.
Adders make processors. Processors run programs. Programs run
languages. Languages let you talk to computers.

That whole tower is what's under Motoi. Twelve or so layers of
abstraction, each one carefully engineered, adding up to something
that can tell you what a lambda is.

Also: the Speak & Spell is the shape of a good learning tool.
Warm, tangible, deterministic, doesn't lie about what it can do,
rewards the kid for showing up. Motoi is trying to be a modern
version of that.")
